of this data, that can apply all the way through.

00:14:55.239 --> 00:14:58.479
So let's illustrate this with a very infamous example, right?

00:14:58.479 --> 00:15:03.780
Let's take Lance Armstrong, most infamous cyclist of all time, famous for doping violations

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:07.760
that he later admitted to and being stripped of all seven Tour de France overall victories,

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:11.460
as well as all UCI World Tour victories.

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:17.700
If I come in to my application as a user, so here in Databricks, we've written a Unity

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:24.599
Catalog filter that says, hey, any convicted cyclist for doping is invisible or not accessible

00:15:24.599 --> 00:15:26.340
to certain users.

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:31.679
So as my user, if I come in and I say, hey, application, how many stages of the Tour de

00:15:31.679 --> 00:15:33.440
France did Lance Armstrong win?

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:36.419
It comes back and says he won 24 stages.

00:15:36.419 --> 00:15:41.239
But if a less-permissioned user logs in and then asks the same question, they get a very

00:15:41.239 --> 00:15:42.679
different response.

00:15:42.679 --> 00:15:44.799
It says zero.

00:15:45.299 --> 00:15:49.340
And then the LLM kind of goes on a journey, because it says, I think Lance did win some

00:15:49.340 --> 00:15:54.260
stages, and so it tries a couple of times to figure out, is his name misspelled?

00:15:54.260 --> 00:15:57.179
Maybe he's organized in here a little bit differently?

00:15:57.179 --> 00:16:00.619
And then finally it comes in and it concludes and says, you know what?

00:16:00.619 --> 00:16:04.539
I can't find any results for Lance Armstrong, and it's probably because he was convicted

00:16:04.539 --> 00:16:07.419
of doping and all of his results were stripped.

00:16:07.419 --> 00:16:13.299
Same application, same URL, two different users, two different answers, because they

00:16:13.299 --> 00:16:16.039
have different permissions in Unity Catalog.

00:16:16.039 --> 00:16:20.679
This allows you to use Unity Catalog as the source of truth for data and data access,

00:16:20.679 --> 00:16:26.000
and then serve an entire collection of business users with a single entry point without needing

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.919
to worry about building in logic for who can see what, because Unity Catalog is already

00:16:29.919 --> 00:16:31.239
taking care of it.

00:16:31.239 --> 00:16:35.359
Not only is this best practice, it also makes the life of the developers a lot easier, because

00:16:35.359 --> 00:16:39.599
one app can now serve multiple audiences within the organization.

00:16:39.599 --> 00:16:42.000
All right.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.820
We've covered a lot of ground, so I want to take just a minute to review a little bit

00:16:44.820 --> 00:16:48.179
about what we've discussed, and then look a little bit towards the future and what we

00:16:48.179 --> 00:16:50.619
see coming up next.

00:16:50.619 --> 00:16:55.539
We propose, and obviously I'm biased, but we propose that Positron is the next generation

00:16:55.539 --> 00:16:57.099
IDE for data scientists.

00:16:57.099 --> 00:17:02.179
We're hard at work on exciting new artificial intelligence features that will make Positron

00:17:02.179 --> 00:17:06.339
an intuitive and natural companion for data scientists who are interactively exploring

00:17:06.339 --> 00:17:08.099
and working with data.

00:17:08.319 --> 00:17:12.280
Databricks OAuth support inside of Posit Workbench and Posit Connect makes it very, very easy

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:17.040
for you to use Unity Catalog to define and govern permission to data, and then for data

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:22.520
scientists, developers, and business users to access data with their appropriate credentials.

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:27.040
Pre-chat's a fabulous new package for building in natural language interfaces to interactive

00:17:27.040 --> 00:17:31.239
applications that can all be powered through Databricks, and you can publish and deploy

00:17:31.339 --> 00:17:38.219
after these applications to both Posit Connect and Databricks apps directly from within Positron.

00:17:38.219 --> 00:17:39.219
So what do we have next?

00:17:39.219 --> 00:17:43.540
We're still working on building out this functionality for one-click publishing to Databricks apps,

00:17:43.540 --> 00:17:47.459
making it as easy as possible for you to build in your preferred environment.

00:17:47.459 --> 00:17:50.500
We would hope that that would be Positron, and then publish that out to Databricks to

00:17:50.500 --> 00:17:53.380
make it accessible across the rest of your organization.

00:17:53.380 --> 00:17:56.780
We're looking to bring Posit tooling into the Databricks ecosystem to make it possible

00:17:56.780 --> 00:18:01.099
to use tools like Positron directly inside your Databricks environment without the need

00:18:01.099 --> 00:18:03.420
to spin up additional infrastructure.

00:18:03.420 --> 00:18:07.599
We're looking to add Databricks support to Positron Assistant so that when you open up

00:18:07.599 --> 00:18:11.420
Positron Assistant and say, help me write this code or help me improve this plot, it's

00:18:11.420 --> 00:18:15.619
working with Cloud Sonnet or whatever model you've chosen within your Databricks account.

00:18:15.619 --> 00:18:18.920
Everything stays inside of that governance platform, and everything's defined by your

00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:19.920
Databricks permissions.

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:23.180
And then one of the things that maybe is a little bit underrated but we're very excited

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:27.640
about is bringing improved SQL support into Positron as well so that it can function not

00:18:27.640 --> 00:18:31.920
only as an editor and tool for R and Python developers, but also those who are working

00:18:31.920 --> 00:18:36.939
directly with SQL and backend data sources like Databricks.

